{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00011","text":"A 2009 study at the University of Ulster found that having sisters, as compared to brothers, can enhance the quality of an adult's life [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_1:11","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00034","text":"Image shows a community bulletin board in Nonguang Village, Sichuan province, China, keeping track of the town's female population, listing recent births by name and noting that several thousand yuan of fines for unauthorized births remain unpaid from the previous year.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_1:34","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00035","text":"There is a preference of parents to have a son over a daughter in many countries [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_1:35","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00062","text":"Chinese government reports show that the sex ratio for newborns is 118:100 (boys:girls), higher in rural areas such as Guangdong and Hainan (130:100) compared to the average of 104:100 in developed countries.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_1:62","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00063","text":"It is believed that the ratio would increase further to the point that, by 2020, men of marriageable age would be unable to find mates, resulting in large social problems [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_1:63","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00080","text":"As China's youngest generation (born under the one-child policy, which first became a requirement for most couples in 1979) came of age for formation of the next generation, a single child would be left with having to provide support for his or her two parents and four grandparents.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_4:80","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00081","text":"In response to this issue, by 2009 all provinces allowed couples to have two children if both parents were only children themselves [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_4:81","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00082","text":"After a policy change of the Chinese government in late 2013, most Chinese provinces further relaxed the policy in 2014 by allowing families to have two children if one of the parents is an only child [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_4:82","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00113","text":"According to The Economist, the new two-child policy may have negative implications on gender roles, with new expectations for women to bear more children and to abandon their careers [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_4:113","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00139","text":"China has been compared to countries such as Thailand, along with the Indian states of Kerala and Tamil Nadu, which experienced similar declines of fertility without a one-child policy [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:139","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00140","text":"Another study takes such arguments even further based on a model which implies that the one-child program, contrary to popular belief and its government's intentions, had a pronatal effect that raised birth rates above what they otherwise would have been [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:140","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00161","text":"That official, Song Jian, along with several associates, determined that the ideal population of China was 700 million, and that a universal one-child policy for all would be required to meet that goal [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:161","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00162","text":"Moreover, Song and his group showed that if fertility rates remained constant at 3 births per woman, China's population would surpass 3 billion by 2060 and 4 billion by 2080 [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:162","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00189","text":"In the words of Wang et al., the idea of the one-child policy came from leaders within the Party, not from scientists who offered evidence to support it”[7] Central officials had already decided in 1979 to advocate for one-child restrictions before knowing of Song's work and, upon learning of his work in 1980, already seemed sympathetic to his position [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:189","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00190","text":"Moreover, even if Song's work convinced them to proceed with universal one-child restrictions in 1980, the policy was loosened to a 1.5-child policy just five years later, and it is that policy which has been misrepresented since as the one-child policy.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:190","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00208","text":"Zhejiang, one of the most affluent provinces, became the first area to implement this relaxed policy in January 2014 [ref], and 29 out of the 31 provinces had implemented it by July 2014 [ref], with the exceptions of Xinjiang and Tibet.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:208","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00209","text":"Under this policy, approximately 11 million couples in China are allowed to have a second child; however, only nearly one million couples applied to have a second child in 2014 [ref], less than half the expected number of 2 million per year [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:209","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00238","text":"The rationale for the abolition was summarized by former Wall Street Journal reporter Mei Fong: The reason China is doing this right now is because they have too many men, too many old people, and too few young people.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:238","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00239","text":"They have this huge crushing demographic crisis as a result of the one-child policy.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:239","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00240","text":"And if people don't start having more children, they're going to have a vastly diminished workforce to support a huge aging population [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:240","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00241","text":"China's ratio is about five working adults to one retiree; the huge retiree community must be supported, and that will dampen future growth, according to Fong.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:241","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00263","text":"Since the citizens of China are living longer and having fewer children, the growth of the population imbalance is expected to continue, as reported by the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation which referred to a United Nations projections forecast that China will lose 67 million working-age people by 2030, while simultaneously doubling the number of elderly.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:263","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00264","text":"That could put immense pressure on the economy and government resources [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:264","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00265","text":"The longer term outlook is also pessimistic, based on an estimate by the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, revealed by Cai Fang, deputy director.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:265","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00266","text":"By 2050, one-third of the country will be aged 60 years or older, and there will be fewer workers supporting each retired person [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:266","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00288","text":"As a result of being an only child, women have increased opportunity to receive an education, and support to get better jobs.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:288","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00289","text":"One of the side effects of the one-child policy is to have liberated women from heavy duties in terms of taking care of many children and the family in the past; instead women had a lot of spare time for themselves to pursue their career or hobbies.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_7:289","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00312","text":"Parents who feel they lost their chance in the Cultural Revolution (compensation syndrome)[1] put immense pressure on these children to succeed and compete academically [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:312","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00313","text":"From an early age parents push their only child to educational extremes as they cater to their whims; though many of these precocious kids can recite the English alphabet or read newspapers in traditional Chinese characters by the time they're 10, their parents often still perform basic tasks for them: fixing their hair, tying their shoes, wiping their bottoms [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:313","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00314","text":"Boarding school, private English lessons, music lessons and an additional range of extracurricular activities are the normal fare [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:314","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00335","text":"The combination of immense pressure to excel and extreme pampering is reported to have resulted in a stunting of social and emotional growth [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:335","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00336","text":"The perceived maladjustment of the little emperors is an exaggerated subject within the media; the government has [tried] to cope with the little emperor problem through frequent cautionary stories in the press [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:336","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00337","text":"These stories depict children hanging themselves after being denied sweets and cases of matricide in retribution for a scolding or late dinner [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:337","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00355","text":"Results from earlier studies are inconsistent with some more recent studies that suggest there are no reliable differences between only children and those with siblings [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:355","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00356","text":"However, a survey published in 2013[14] on 431 Beijing adults finds that those who had grown up after the introduction of the one-child policy were lacking entrepreneurial drive and the willingness to take risks [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:356","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00357","text":"This even had a significant impact on career choices [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_9:357","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00365","text":"Women's reproductive rights may include some or all of the following: the right to legal and safe abortion; the right to birth control; freedom from coerced sterilization and contraception; the right to access good-quality reproductive healthcare; and the right to education and access in order to make free and informed reproductive choices [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_10:365","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00388","text":"Reproductive rights began to appear as a subset of human rights in the 1968 Proclamation of Tehran, which states: Parents have a basic human right to determine freely and responsibly the number and the spacing of their children [ref].","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_10:388","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00415","text":"The non-binding Programme of Action asserted that governments have a responsibility to meet individuals' reproductive needs, rather than demographic targets.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_10:415","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
{"record_id":"iam-evidence-00434","text":"Reproductive rights embrace certain human rights that are already recognized in national laws, international human rights documents and other relevant United Nations consensus documents.","provider":"iam_integrated_argument_mining","source_type":"human_calibration","claim_label":"claim","premise_label":"evidence","relation_label":"support","confidence":1.0,"source_dataset":"IAM evidence/train.txt","source_record_id":"1_10:434","source_url":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LiyingCheng95/IAM/main/evidence/train.txt","human_labelled":true}
